From a95c7bc929d37f161a4c7f6a33fcfd07d5e499e2 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Nathan Brake <33383515+njbrake@users.noreply.github.com>
Date: Sun, 8 Mar 2026 07:25:23 -0700
Subject: [PATCH 071/117] fix: delete sandbox worktree contents via container
 to avoid permission denied (#405)

Sandbox containers run as root, so files they create (build artifacts in
target/, etc.) are root-owned on the host. On macOS Docker Desktop, the
file sharing layer doesn't propagate permission changes from inside the
container to the host, so chmod-based approaches don't work.

Instead, delete the worktree contents from inside the still-running
container (where root can remove root-owned files), then clean up the
empty directory and git metadata on the host via git worktree prune.

Also removes convert_git_file_to_absolute (added in #400) which was
attempting to fix this same permission denied error by converting
relative .git paths back to absolute before removal. The actual cause
was always root-owned files, not path resolution -- git handles relative
gitdir paths fine during worktree removal (confirmed by the fact that
non-sandboxed worktrees with relative paths delete without issue).

Co-authored-by: Claude Opus 4.6 <noreply@anthropic.com>
